  "demonstrative_examples": [
    {
      "text": "\n               \u003cIntro_Text\u003eIf a Servlet does not catch all exceptions, it may reveal debugging information that will help an adversary form a plan of attack. In the following method a DNS lookup failure will cause the Servlet to throw an exception.\u003c/Intro_Text\u003e\n               \u003cExample_Code Nature=\"bad\" Language=\"Java\"\u003e\n                  \u003cxhtml:div\u003eprotected void doPost (HttpServletRequest req, HttpServletResponse res) throws IOException {\u003cxhtml:div style=\"margin-left:10px;\"\u003eString ip = req.getRemoteAddr();\u003cxhtml:br/\u003eInetAddress addr = InetAddress.getByName(ip);\u003cxhtml:br/\u003e...\u003cxhtml:br/\u003eout.println(\"hello \" + addr.getHostName());\u003c/xhtml:div\u003e}\u003c/xhtml:div\u003e\n               \u003c/Example_Code\u003e\n               \u003cBody_Text\u003eWhen a Servlet throws an exception, the default error response the Servlet container sends back to the user typically includes debugging information. This information is of great value to an attacker.\u003c/Body_Text\u003e\n            "
    }
  ],
